An Exploration of Network Analysis Through Macbeth

Julis Koch

31/12/2021

INTRODUCTION

Shakespeare’s Macbeth is marked by a number of murders. Much of it occurs due Macbeth’s fear of loss of power and status as reign; his wife, Lady Macbeth, supporting him in intrigues against his closest allies. As Banquo’s throat is sliced, Duncan stabbed in the back,Macdownald is executed, and Siward stabbed, whilst Lady Macbeth eventually commits suicide with Macbeth ultimately beheaded. The lethal mix of suspicion and thirst for power have been described as tragic (Shanley, 1961) and as karmic (Desmond, 2002) in public scholarship, with the fundamental question being: where does evil reside, internally or externally (Islam, 2010: 191-192)?

Whilst perhaps karmic or malicious in nature, and tragic in consequence, social network analysis may help provide a more social structural analysis of death. More specifically, it suggest that evil may be the result of social interaction and plot, as I am going to show in the following.

DATASET AND LIMITATIONS

The dataset of Shakespeare’s Macbeth was extracted from https://github.com/mallaham/Shakespeare-Plays. I did not verify completion or factual accuracy, which is why the number of characters may vary from the original play. Due to time constraints and feasibility, the network presented is unidirectional, defined by co-appearance and first speaker. Accordingly, response and further interaction is not captured appropriately. Moreover, while I initially accounted for attributes such as gender, cause.of.death and power, these did not translate into the network simulations as desired. I have hence broadened the scope of inquiry. This piece can thus be considered an explorational network analysis of what not to research, confirming ‘social fundamentals’ and pointing out future aspects of network analysis of Shakespeare’s plays instead. Finally, the ERGM model only partially converted - with the Markov calculation excluded from the code.

HYPOTHESIS

H1 Interactions in Macbeth are random, such that intrigues and murder cannot be inferred.

H2 Malicious behaviour may be characterised by unidirectional interaction, as is expressed, for instance, in a comparatively low probability coefficient when observing a tie in a diad.

H3 Regardless, the clustering of individuals reflects findings of established eigenvector nodes.

The p-value of < 0.001 indicates strong significance for the ties to not occur at random; the specific value of AIC and BIC would need to be further explored in additional models to establish model fit at this stage.

The corresponding probability of a tie change is -1.987583; with the probability of a tie in a dIad being fairly low, namely at 0.1205128. This statistic would also allow for a conclusion on the density of the network, but I aNd discussing this aspect later on.

The simulation of edge-wise shared partners is not as accurate, with an inital over-estimation from edge-wise shared partners 0-1, and an underestimation until edgewise-shared partners 8; from 10 we observe absolute fit.

The goodness of fit for triad census is even more accurate mostly convering from 102 onwards, with only a brief overestimation between 021U and 111D.

With the p-value at .96, which approximates 1, the goodness of fit of this ergm model is generally given.

H1 is disproven overall, implying relevance of also the following findings.

MALICIOUS BEHAVIOUR AND DYADIC TIES

## [1] 0.1205128
## [1] 0.1914894
## [1] 0.1058824

With 0.12 the network density can be considered scarce; this is also reflected in the the fairly low number of unidirectional (0.19) and reciprocal dyadic interactions (0.11) between characters.

It suggests little collaboration and fairly instantaneous interaction across the course of the play.

## [1] 0.4945706

While the Markov ERGM Model did not converge, and I could therefore not test for triadic interaction, the network represents a fairly high coefficient for transitivity, suggesting a somewhat high number connected of characters in the form of ‘via-via-acquaintances’ regardless.

STRONG COMPONENTS OR CLUSTERS OF POWER?

Interestingly, this network is comprised of a surprisingly high number of strong components or individuals (orange), with only a few characters (colourful) being less well connected and fairly removed. The latter represent the weak components of the network.

It may thus be difficult to single out nodes of influence and intrigue among this high number of strong components.

Interestingly, the largest cluster (red) represents 6 out of 7 individuals with the highest eigenvector score: Macbeth, Banquo, Lennox, Ross, Macduff and Malcolm are all clustered together - only Lady Macbeth belong to a different but neighbouring cluster, yellow.

These findings suggest that many of the most powerful people are within proximity, and closely connected.

Interestingly, however, of the seven most powerful individuals, only two of the three most powerful (Macbeth and Banquo) are murdered, as is Lady Macbeth; Lennox, Ross, Macduff and Malcolm have at least a 1/3 if not 1/2 the size of their eigenvector coefficient stay alive.

CONCLUSION

I have been able to show that in this scarce network of Macbeth characters, no tie is coincidental (H1). Regardless, however, much of the interaction between characters is unidirectional, transitive, but not necessarily dyadic (H2). It may suggest less coordinated intrigue and subsequent action, which surround scenes of murder, or constitute ‘evil’(H2).

What has become evident, is that the powerful are closely clustered (H3).

FUTURE RESEARCH

As mentioned above, additional attributes may contribute to a more nuanced and insightful study of what contributes to ‘the evil and malicious’ in Shakespeare’s Macbeth, socially speaking.

Moreover, panel data and longitudinal network analysis may demonstrate the evolution of characters’ relationships across various acts.

Regardless, from what we have been able to observe thus far, dis-organised, and loosely tied groups may be considered the norm for lethal intrigues in Macbeth; even if the most powerful are within each others’ proximity.
